                <head>No. 666<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On August 4, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> arrived in
                    the Republic of Korea for talks with President <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName>. On August 8, <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>
                    left Seoul for an overnight visit to Tokyo, after which he returned to the
                    United States.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName> discussed Japan-Korea issues during their meeting on August
                    5. <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> complained that it was not wise to
                    build up Japan economically and militarily. <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName> replied that the United States-Korea Mutual Defense
                    Treaty would protect Korea from <pb facs="0412" n="1468" xml:id="pg_1468"/>
                    Japan as well as from the Soviet Union, that the United States no more than
                    Korea wanted Japan to become again “a dominant power,” and that Japanese-Korean
                    cooperation was needed for the security of the Western Pacific. For the
                    memorandum of this conversation, see <ref target="frus1952-54v15p2#pg_1466"
                        >volume XV, page 1466</ref>. For discussion of Japan at the <persName
                        corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName> meeting held August 6, see <ref target="#d671">Document
                        671</ref>.</p>
            </div>
